Github Tutorial

GitHub is a web-based platform used for version control and collaborative software development. It provides a centralized location for developers to store, manage, and collaborate on their code, and it has become one of the most popular platforms for open-source software development.

GitHub provides the following features:

Version Control: It uses Git as its version control system, which allows developers to track changes to their code over time and collaborate with others on their codebase.

Collaboration: GitHub provides a platform for developers to collaborate on their code, by sharing their code with others, creating and reviewing pull requests, and managing issues and bugs.

Hosting: GitHub provides a place for developers to host their code, making it accessible to others and providing a backup of their work.

Project Management: GitHub provides tools for managing projects, including project boards, milestones, and issues.

Integrations: GitHub integrates with many other tools and services, such as CI/CD systems, chat tools, and project management tools.

GitHub is free for public repositories, and it offers paid plans for private repositories and enterprise-level features. It also has a large community of users and contributors, making it a popular choice for developers and organizations of all sizes.



